# Three Stone Pear Diamond Ring: The Complete {{year}} Guide

## TL;DR — Key Facts at a Glance

- Three stone pear diamond ring settings start at **$1,820** (Pear Sidestone, 63 reviews) — the most field-tested pear sidestone setting in the Blue Nile catalog
- Pear diamonds appear in three-stone rings in two roles: as the **center stone** flanked by baguette, marquise, trillion, or emerald sides — or as **side stones** flanking an oval, cushion, or round center
- **The Mirror Rule**: pear side stone tips must point outward (away from the center stone) — inward-pointing pear tips create visual tension and are a correctable design error
- The most searched three-stone pear configuration: oval center + pear side stones in yellow gold (880 monthly searches)
- Marquise Cut Three Stone by James Allen (152 reviews, $1,970) is the most-reviewed three-stone setting for a pear center stone in the Blue Nile catalog
- Complete three-stone pear rings (1ct center + pear side setting) start at **~$2,620** with a lab stone and **~$4,970** with a natural GIA-certified stone

---

A three stone pear diamond ring is one of the most visually complex ring configurations available. It involves decisions about center stone shape, side stone shape, the proportion ratio between them, and the orientation of the pear's asymmetrical silhouette — all at once.

The pear diamond plays two distinct roles in three-stone rings. As a center stone, it presents an asymmetrical silhouette that side stones must complement without competing. As a side stone, two mirrored pears flank a center stone — typically oval, round, or cushion cut — and the orientation of each pear tip determines whether the ring reads as intentional design or a correctable error.

This guide covers both roles in full: every three-stone setting Blue Nile offers that involves a pear diamond, the two named frameworks that govern how pear diamonds work in multi-stone rings, and complete pricing across every carat tier and metal.

---

## What Is a Three Stone Pear Diamond Ring?

A three stone pear diamond ring features one center stone and two side stones, where the pear cut appears in at least one of the three positions. The pear's asymmetrical teardrop silhouette — one rounded belly tapering to a pointed tip — creates specific design requirements that distinguish these rings from three-stone rings using symmetrical cuts.

There are three primary configurations:

**Pear center + symmetrical sides:** The pear is the center stone, flanked by baguette, marquise, trillion, half-moon, trapezoid, or emerald cuts. Shapes that contrast linearly with the pear center — baguette, emerald — create Art Deco tension. Shapes that echo it organically — trillion, marquise — create a unified directional field.

**Symmetrical center + pear sides:** An oval, round, cushion, or other center stone is flanked by two mirrored pear-shaped side stones. This "pear sidestone" configuration is the most-searched three-stone pear variant. The oval center with pear sides dominates this category because oval and pear share the same curved design language.

**All-pear or multi-pear configurations:** Two or three pear diamonds in the same ring — toi et moi, five-stone fan, or cluster arrangements. Less common in the Blue Nile configurable catalog; available through custom fabrication.

The configuration you choose changes the visual center of gravity entirely. Pear side stones make the center stone the focal point, amplified by a fanning frame. A pear center in a three-stone setting competes with its sides unless proportions are carefully controlled.

[![Three stone pear diamond ring in rose gold — Blue Nile pear sidestone setting](/images/three-stone-pear-diamond-ring-rose-gold.avif)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?styleIDs=three_stone&MetalType=all&Diamonds=Dia&ShapeID=Pear&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

---

## The Mirror Rule: Why Pear Side Stone Orientation Determines Everything

**The Mirror Rule** is the principle that pear-shaped side stones must be oriented with their pointed tips facing outward — away from the center stone, toward the ends of the band — to create a coherent three-stone design.

The logic is directional. A pear diamond has a pointed end and a rounded end. When two mirrored pear side stones face each other with tips pointing inward toward the center, the eye reads two arrows targeting the center stone. This creates visual tension — the side stones appear to squeeze or attack the center rather than frame it.

When the pear tips point outward, the opposite happens. The rounded belly of each pear naturally embraces the curve of the center stone (most effectively with oval or round centers), while the tapered ends draw the eye along the band in both directions. The ring reads as expansive and intentional. Every configurable Blue Nile pear sidestone setting follows The Mirror Rule by default; any custom or hand-set ring that does not is a correctable design error — take it back to the jeweler.

[![Three stone pear diamond ring white gold lifestyle view — Blue Nile](/images/three-stone-pear-diamond-ring-white-gold-lifestyle.avif)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?styleIDs=three_stone&MetalType=all&Diamonds=Dia&ShapeID=Pear&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

---

## The Three-Stone Ratio: Getting Side Stone Weight Right

**The Three-Stone Ratio** is the framework for matching side stone carat weight to the center stone in any three-stone pear configuration.

The rule: combined side stone weight should be **30–40% of the center stone's carat weight**. For a 1ct center, target 0.30–0.40ct total in side stones — approximately 0.15–0.20ct per side. This ratio creates visual balance where the center reads as primary and the sides read as frame.

Going above 50% creates a tri-cluster effect: three equal-looking stones with no clear center. Going below 20% makes side stones read as large pavé accent diamonds rather than true sidestones. The two Blue Nile pear sidestone settings — 1/4ct total ($1,820) and 1/2ct total ($4,750) — are calibrated specifically for center stones at 0.65–0.85ct and 1.25–1.65ct respectively.

| Side Stone Total | Recommended Center Range | Setting to Use |
|-----------------|------------------------|----------------|
| 1/4 ct. tw. (0.25ct) | 0.65–0.85ct center | Pear Sidestone $1,820 |
| 1/3 ct. tw. (0.33ct) | 0.85–1.10ct center | Trillion, Tapered Baguette |
| 1/2 ct. tw. (0.50ct) | 1.25–1.65ct center | Classic Pear Sidestone $4,750 |
| 5/8 ct. tw. (0.62ct) | 1.55–2.00ct center | Premium Baguette, Emerald |

