## Oval Diamond With Pear Side Stones: The Dominant Configuration

The oval center with pear side stones is the most searched three-stone pear configuration at 880 monthly searches — and the most visually cohesive one. Oval and pear share a common design language: both are elongated stones with curved silhouettes and no sharp corners. The belly of each pear side stone naturally echoes the curve of the oval center when The Mirror Rule is followed.

This combination works for a specific visual reason: the three stones share a continuous curved line from one pear tip across the oval's length to the other pear tip. When well-proportioned, the viewer perceives a flowing, uninterrupted diamond silhouette rather than three separate stones. No other center cut creates this effect as naturally.

**Proportioning oval + pear:** Pear side stones should be approximately 60–70% of the oval's length. For a 1ct oval measuring approximately 9mm × 7mm, ideal pear side stones are 6–7mm long. Shorter side stones look stubby against an elongated oval; longer ones overwhelm it.

Yellow gold is the dominant metal choice for this combination in {{year}}. The warm metal creates a vintage, Art Deco-adjacent aesthetic that complements both shapes. The [Pear Sidestone Diamond Engagement Ring in 14k Yellow Gold](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/pear-sidestone-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-yellow-gold-1-4-ct-tw-item-192877?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) ($1,820, 63 reviews) is the starting point. At 63 reviews it is the most field-tested pear sidestone setting in the catalog. The [Metal Multiplier Effect explained in the pear settings guide](/pear-shaped-diamond-ring) applies here — an H-color oval center in yellow gold saves $400–$800 vs. the G you'd need in white gold.

---

## Cushion Cut Diamond With Pear Side Stones

A cushion center with pear side stones creates deliberate visual contrast. The cushion's square-adjacent silhouette with rounded corners creates a blocky center profile; the elongated pear side stones stretch the ring horizontally in a way that contrasts with rather than echoes the center. This is not wrong — it is a fashion-forward choice where the contrast between cushion and pear is the design statement.

The rounded corners of the cushion meet the rounded belly of each pear side stone at the shoulders, creating a soft transition between stones. **For cushion + pear combinations:** pear side stones should be narrower than for an oval center — approximately 50–60% of the cushion's diameter — to maintain the cushion's visual dominance. Wider pear sides overpower a cushion center.

The [Classic Pear Shaped Diamond Engagement Ring in Platinum (1/2 ct. tw.)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/classic-pear-shaped-diamond-engagement-ring-in-platinum-1-2-ct-tw-item-194314?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) ($4,750, 41 reviews) is the premium pear sidestone setting for larger cushion or round centers (1.25ct+). At 1/2ct total side stone weight in platinum, it is calibrated for the Three-Stone Ratio at this center size and provides maximum prong security for daily wear.

---

## Pear and Emerald Cut Diamond Ring

The pear + emerald combination sits at the intersection of two opposed design philosophies: the pear is curved, asymmetrical, brilliant-cut; the emerald is rectangular, symmetrical, step-cut. Their pairing creates sharp, intentional contrast.

**Emerald center + pear side stones:** A classic Art Deco-inspired configuration. The rectangular emerald center's clear, glassy step facets are framed by two outward-pointing pear side stones. For true pear sides flanking an emerald center, the Pear Sidestone settings ($1,820, 63 reviews) are the primary catalog option.

**Pear center + emerald side stones:** The [Three-Stone Emerald Cut Engagement Ring in 14K White Gold (5/8 ct. tw.)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/three-stone-emerald-cut-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-5-8-ct-tw-item-203648?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) ($4,510, 4 reviews) places substantial emerald-cut sides beside a pear center. The rectangular emerald sides create a stabilizing horizontal anchor for the asymmetrical pear. The [Zac Zac Posen Three-Stone Emerald Cut in 14k Yellow Gold](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/zac-zac-posen-three-stone-emerald-cut-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-yellow-gold-1-3-ct-tw-item-203528?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) ($3,460, 9 reviews) offers the same configuration with a designer name in yellow gold.

---

## Pear With Trillion Side Stones

Trillion side stones (triangular cut diamonds) create a botanical, organic three-stone relationship with a pear center. Both the pear and trillion are non-rectangular stones with at least one acute angle — their shared vocabulary creates a unified, nature-inspired aesthetic that baguette or emerald sides cannot replicate.

The [Three-Stone Trillion Diamond Engagement Ring in Platinum (1/3 ct. tw.)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/three-stone-trillion-diamond-engagement-ring-in-platinum-1-3-ct-tw-item-192950?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) ($3,840, 4 reviews) is the most durable trillion side stone option. Platinum holds trillion prongs more securely over decades than 14k gold — and trillion prongs are structurally more vulnerable than round stone prongs due to the sharp apex. The [Three-Stone Trillion in 14k Rose Gold (1/3 ct. tw.)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/three-stone-trillion-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-rose-gold-1-3-ct-tw-item-203662?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) ($3,255, 4 reviews) creates the most romantic pear + trillion combination — three organic shapes in warm rose gold.

---

## Marquise and Pear Diamond Ring

The marquise and pear combination is the most dynamically matched pairing in three-stone design. Both are elongated fancy cuts with points — the marquise has two pointed ends; the pear has one. When marquise side stones flank a pear center, the result is a ring with three elongated stones creating a unified directional visual field.

The key is preventing marquise side stones from overwhelming the pear center. The marquise has two visible points; apply The Three-Stone Ratio strictly — marquise side stones should not exceed 35% of center stone weight for a pear + marquise combination. Exceeding this threshold shifts the visual weight away from the pear center toward the pointed side stones.

The [Marquise Cut Diamond Three Stone Engagement Ring by James Allen in 14k Yellow Gold](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/marquise-cut-diamond-three-stone-engagement-ring-in-14k-yellow-gold-by-james-allen-item-315107?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) ($1,970, 152 reviews) is the most-reviewed three-stone setting in the entire Blue Nile catalog that accepts a pear center stone. It is also available in [white gold](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/marquise-cut-diamond-three-stone-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-by-james-allen-item-315103?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and [rose gold](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/marquise-cut-diamond-three-stone-engagement-ring-in-14k-rose-gold-by-james-allen-item-315100?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), all at $1,970. 152 reviews across metal variants represents more real buyer feedback than any other three-stone setting here.

