> "The three-stone pear ring is the most demanding ring in the catalog to get right — and the most rewarding when the proportions are correct. The Mirror Rule eliminates the most common mistake before it happens. The Three-Stone Ratio eliminates the second-most-common mistake.
>
> After those two decisions, the question is just: is the pear the story, or is it the frame? Pear as center — choose contrasting linear side stones. Pear as side stone — choose a curved center that speaks the same visual language. Oval is almost always right.
>
> And always, always start with the setting that has the most reviews. In the pear sidestone category, 63 reviews beats intuition." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

